item.title: EU Plans $2 Trillion Coronavirus Response Effort
item.description: The bloc proposed an $824 billion recovery plan and a $1.2 trillion budget over the next seven years, which, if approved, would deepen its economic union in a way that even the eurozone debt crisis failed to achieve.

item.title: Canadian Judge Rules U.S. Met Legal Test to Seek Huawei Executive's Extradition
item.description: A Canadian judge ruled that the U.S. met a key legal test to seek the extradition of a senior Huawei Technologies executive who has been at the center of a fight between Washington and Beijing over the giant telecom-equipment maker.

item.title: U.S. Officially Declares That Hong Kong Is No Longer Autonomous
item.description: The State Department has officially determined that Hong Kong is no longer autonomous from China, Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said in a statement that holds implications for the future of economic ties and could lead to sanctions against China.

item.title: India's Migrants Head Home as Lockdown Eases, Prompting Fears of Spread
item.description: More than 10 million of Indiaâ€™s suddenly jobless migrant workers are moving from cities back to their home villages, a historic reverse-migration that brings with it concerns about a new wave of coronavirus cases and social unrest in some of the poorest, least prepared places.

item.title: Brazil's Daily Coronavirus Death Toll Surpasses That of U.S.
item.description: Brazil has reached a grim milestone, reporting more Covid-19 deaths in one day than the U.S., which until recently had logged the most daily fatalities from the disease.

item.title: 'Vaccine Nationalism': New Dynamic in the Race to Quash Coronavirus
item.description: Pharmaceutical companies are bracing for export bans on future coronavirus vaccines and spreading production across different continents, on early signs of a geopolitical scramble to secure supplies.
